Package data

Class ConstructedData

java.lang.Object
data.ConstructedData
public class ConstructedData
extends java.lang.Object
This class provides a selection methods to generate datasets that can be used to test embedding methods.
Author:
Anton Ballmaier

  • Method Details

    • randomSwissRoll

      public static double[][] randomSwissRoll​(int n)
      Generates a so called swiss roll dataset. This dataset consists of points lying on a spiraling 2d surface in 3d space. The points within this dataset are generated randomly with a uniform distribution.
      Parameters:
      n - the number of points to generate
      Returns:
      the swiss roll dataset

    • randomWalks

      public static Polygon[] randomWalks​(int amount)
      Generates a Polygon dataset where each polygon is a random walk starting at the origin. Their length ranges from 3 to 15, the dimension of the polygon space is 4. The amount of Polygons can be specified.
      Parameters:
      amount - the number of Polygons to generate
      Returns:
      the generated Polygons

    • randomWalks

      public static Polygon[] randomWalks​(int amount, int minLength, int maxLength, int dimensions)
      Generates a Polygon dataset where each polygon is a random walk starting at the origin. The length, dimension of the polygon space and amount of Polygons can be specified.
      Parameters:
      amount - the number of Polygons to generate
      minLength - the minimum length
      maxLength - the maximum length
      dimensions - the dimension of the polygon space
      Returns:
      the generated Polygons

    • shiftedSpikes

      public static Polygon[] shiftedSpikes​(double range, double step)
      Generates a dataset of Polygons. They lie on a 2d manifold in the 2d polygon space and have length 5. The Polygons within this dataset are distributed evenly.

      Every Polygon is generated from two parameters a and b. All parameter values from a certain interval, separated by a certain step size are chosen.

      Parameters:
      range - defines the interval from which the parameter values are selected. The interval used is [-range, range].
      step - the difference between two used parameter values
      Returns:
      the generated dataset
